# MotoAuction Deployment Guide

Deploying a real-time WebSocket application requires a slightly different approach than a standard static website. Because this platform uses **Spring Boot**, **PostgreSQL**, **Redis**, and **WebSockets**, we recommend a split-deployment strategy for maximum performance and cost-effectiveness.

---

## 🏗️ Architecture Overview

Your application is split into two halves:
1. **The Frontend:** A static React (Vite) application.
2. **The Backend:** A containerized Spring Boot engine running alongside PostgreSQL and Redis databases.

---

## 🟢 Part 1: Deploying the Frontend (Vercel)

**Recommended Platform:** [Vercel](https://vercel.com) or [Netlify](https://netlify.com)
**Why?** They are completely free, automatically deploy from GitHub, and serve static React files via global CDNs so your website loads instantly anywhere in the world.

### Steps:
1. **Push to GitHub:** Commit and push your entire codebase to a GitHub repository.
2. **Create a Vercel Account:** Go to Vercel.com and log in with GitHub.
3. **Import Project:** Click "Add New Project" and select your repository.
4. **Configure the Build:**
   * **Framework Preset:** Vercel will automatically detect `Vite`.
   * **Root Directory:** Edit this and set it to `frontend` (since your React code is inside the `frontend` folder, not the root).
   * **Build Command:** `npm run build`
   * **Output Directory:** `dist`
5. **Environment Variables:**
   * Add a new variable: `VITE_API_URL`
   * Value: `https://api.yourbackend.com/api` *(You will update this later once your backend is deployed).*
6. **Deploy:** Click deploy. Your frontend is now live on a public URL!

---

## 🔴 Part 2: Deploying the Backend (Render)

**Recommended Platform:** [Render.com](https://render.com)
**Why?** Render automatically builds your Spring Boot Docker container directly from GitHub, and provides managed, one-click setups for both PostgreSQL and Redis. They handle the SSL certificates (HTTPS) for you automatically!

### Steps:

#### 1. Setup the Databases (PostgreSQL & Redis)
1. Log in to Render.com.
2. Click **New +** -> **PostgreSQL**. Name it `auction-db`. Click **Create Database**.
3. Click **New +** -> **Redis**. Name it `auction-redis`. Click **Create Redis**.
4. Once both are created, find their **Internal Database URLs**. (Render allows services on the same account to talk securely to each other using internal URLs).

#### 2. Deploy the Spring Boot API (Web Service)
1. Click **New +** -> **Web Service**.
2. Connect your GitHub repository containing the backend code.
3. **Environment:** Choose `Docker`.
4. Render will automatically detect your `Dockerfile`. 
5. Scroll down to **Environment Variables** and add the variables your Spring Boot app needs to connect to the databases you just created:
   * `SPRING_DATASOURCE_URL`: `jdbc:postgresql://<your-internal-postgres-url>`
   * `SPRING_DATASOURCE_USERNAME`: `<your-db-username>`
   * `SPRING_DATASOURCE_PASSWORD`: `<your-db-password>`
   * `SPRING_REDIS_HOST`: `<your-internal-redis-host>`
   * `SPRING_REDIS_PORT`: `<your-redis-port>`
6. Click **Create Web Service**. Render will now download your code, build the Docker container, and start it!

---

## 🔗 Part 3: Connecting Them Together

Since you used Render for the backend and Vercel for the frontend, both services automatically give you secure `https://` URLs, which means WebSockets will work out of the box without any complex Nginx or SSL setup!

1. **Get your Render API URL:** 
   * Go to your Render Web Service dashboard.
   * Copy the public URL provided at the top left (e.g., `https://auction-backend-xyz.onrender.com`).
2. **Update CORS in Backend (Optional but Recommended):**
   * If your Spring Boot app has a hardcoded CORS policy, ensure it allows requests from your new Vercel domain. You can pass the Vercel domain as another Environment Variable in Render if your code supports it.
3. **Update Frontend:**
   * Go back to your Vercel Dashboard for your frontend project.
   * Go to **Settings** -> **Environment Variables**.
   * Update the `VITE_API_URL` to point to your new Render backend URL:
     * Value: `https://auction-backend-xyz.onrender.com/api`
   * Trigger a **Redeploy** in Vercel to lock in the new variable.

**🎉 Congratulations! Your real-time MotoAuction platform is now securely deployed and live on the internet!**
